T1  - The Interrelationship of Intrinsic and Extrinsic Motivation
AU  - Dermer, Jerry
Y1  - 1975/03/01
PY  - 1975
DA  - 1975/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255630
DO  - 10.5465/255630
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 125
EP  - 129
VL  - 18
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article discusses the interrelationship of intrinsic and extrinsic motivation. In many organizations, budget performance is used as the basis for allocating extrinsic rewards while budget motivation is motivation for performance-contingent rewards. The author suggests that intrinsic motivation is not reduced in the presence of performance-contingent extrinsic rewards, as it is a necessary prerequisite for performance-contingent rewards to be motivating. The general assumption of many motivational researchers is that intrinsic and extrinsic motivation are independent of each other. A study is looked at with the purpose of aiding management in resolving performance rewards problems through the context of a budget system.
AB  - The article discusses the interrelationship of intrinsic and extrinsic motivation. In many organizations, budget performance is used as the basis for allocating extrinsic rewards while budget motivation is motivation for performance-contingent rewards. The author suggests that intrinsic motivation is not reduced in the presence of performance-contingent extrinsic rewards, as it is a necessary prerequisite for performance-contingent rewards to be motivating. The general assumption of many motivational researchers is that intrinsic and extrinsic motivation are independent of each other. A study is looked at with the purpose of aiding management in resolving performance rewards problems through the context of a budget system.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255630
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255630
Y2  - 2026/04/24
